# Files are truth, databases are projections

## Decision

The system of record for Brain content — including observation pages from the
observational-memory write loop — is **the filesystem: `.svx` files in git
repositories**, synced fleet-wide through dark-wizard. Databases on flagg
(Postgres, Redis, Typesense, ClickHouse, graph.json, and whatever arrives
next) hold only **rebuildable projections** of those files. Every projection
must be deletable and reconstructible from the repos; no projection may be
the only home of durable knowledge.

## Why

1. **The substrate insight**: the network of git repositories IS the
   multi-machine story — replication, history, diffs, conflict semantics,
   and provenance for free. Database-as-truth reopens sync/backup/offline
   problems git already solved, to get worse provenance.
2. **The read side assumes files**: the brain.joelclaw.com renderer reads
   checkouts; graph.json projects from files; wikilinks resolve between
   files; the `.svx` law exists because files are pages. A row in Postgres
   doesn't render, doesn't link, and can't be `Read` by an agent.
3. **Volume doesn't argue**: ~43 qualifying sessions/day ≈ 15k observation
   pages/year. Git handles that without noticing, for years.

This extends the graph-store research resolution ("promote a real store only
on measured need") from the graph to all Brain/memory storage.

## Named exit triggers (decision has an exit, not dogma)

- Multi-writer contention on observation repos (the single flagg observer
  avoids this by design — revisit if observers multiply).
- Query patterns the Typesense + graph projections genuinely can't serve
  (e.g. temporal aggregation across tens of thousands of observations).
- Sustained volume past ~100 pages/day.

Even then, the presumptive answer is a fatter **projection** (ClickHouse),
not moving custody.

## One-liner

Flagg's databases all deserve jobs — just not custody.
